  "text": "Denote by S n (\u00b5) = {i : 1 \u2264 i \u2264 n, \u00b5 i \u0338 = 0} the set of all non-zero components of \u00b5. We focus on the case of sparse signals when S n (\u00b5) constitutes a very small share of n; throughout this paper it is assumed that S n (\u00b5) \u2264 n 1\u2212\u03b2 for all n large enough and some \u03b2 from (0, 1/3). Since it is not known beforehand which components of \u00b5 are not zero, the value of loss function (in the sense of (7) below) 236 ANDREY ORDIN in model (1) exceeds n 1\u2212\u03b2 . Moreover, reasonably precise estimations of the set S n (\u00b5) require additional assumptions on the vector \u00b5 (see, e.g., [CITATION_1] ). On the other hand, under adaptive sampling these assumptions may be significantly relaxed. We will restrict our attention to the signals \u00b5 from the set",
